  "runtime_verified": false,
  "_comment": "WIN-SYS-015 Help/About & legacy/optional-feature dialogs. A composition-PINNING contract (calc-chrome idiom) over existing upstream cui .ui files -- there is no per-dialog Material .cxx to guard; the Material treatment is delivered by the shared vcl parts and the shared link/notification machinery pinned elsewhere. Three layers, all py-static, runtime_verified false throughout: (1) anatomy_pinned pins the informational Help/About family anatomy -- aboutdialog.ui (modal GtkDialog, single btnClose dismiss response -7, the four GtkLinkButton link surfaces) and tipofthedaydialog.ui (navigational btnNext/btnLink, single btnOk dismiss response -5); tipofthedaydialog declares no .ui modal property, so its modal claim is keyed off the CSV KeepModal policy row, NOT a .ui property. (2) notification_policy cross-checks the shared dialog-notification-policy.csv keeps the About/Tip rows native-exclusion (KeepModal), and no_destructive_role asserts the family never appears as a destructive migration in dialog-anatomy-policy.json. (3) family + ui_registry cross-reads ui-registry.json and fails closed if any of the 16 WIN-SYS-015 UI-file surfaces drifts off inventory_id=WIN-SYS-015 / mapped_by=override (the registry-progress the row's REGISTRY gate measures: the 15 cui surfaces were moved out of the 449-entry unassigned baseline, joining the pre-existing vcl/aboutbox.ui override). The legacy/optional cui surfaces (hyperlink/thesaurus/hyphenate/hangul-hanja/expert-config) are owner-level attribution only; per-surface anatomy is deferred.",
  "policy_registry": "qa/windows-ui-contract/dialog-notification-policy.csv",
  "anatomy_registry": "qa/windows-ui-contract/dialog-anatomy-policy.json",
  "ui_registry": "qa/windows-ui-contract/ui-registry.json",
  "inventory_id": "WIN-SYS-015",
